  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "ZXm68HIvWAsMVZzd1zyqdCHdkjo=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:38.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Batch payload shape\n\nEach operation batch uploaded to `/bytes` is an encrypted JSON array of `OperationWithContext`:\n\n```\n{\n  operation: {\n    id: \"c6401aec-...\",\n    index: 0,\n    skip: 0,\n    timestampUtcMs: \"2026-04-11T18:06:34.210Z\",\n    hash: \"gfgqmD...\",\n    action: {\n      type: \"CREATE_DOCUMENT\",\n      input: { name: \"push\", model: \"powerhouse/document-model\", ... },\n      scope: \"document\",\n      context: { signer: { user: { address: \"0xadbA7C2F...\" } } }\n    }\n  },\n  context: {\n    documentId: \"57033542-...\",\n    documentType: \"powerhouse/document-model\",\n    scope: \"document\",\n    branch: \"main\",\n    ordinal: 5\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## Why this shape matters\n\n- `operation.id` is stable across replays \u2014 recovery produces the same op IDs.\n- `action.context.signer.signatures` is preserved verbatim, so authorship stays intact across device migration.\n- `context.ordinal` is the global ordinal from `operation_index_operations`, enabling deterministic ordering even when batches arrive out of order.\n- The reference address is a **content hash** of the ciphertext, so identical batches deduplicate naturally on Swarm.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:38.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:38.000Z"
    }
  },
